<br>
GW does indeed care enough about the independant retailers to do this.  It's at the independant retailer where people see the games played or play a demo, decide to play themselves, and start buying.  GW actually has their head screwed on right in this regard - to such a degree that they deliberately don't put a lot of playing area in their own stores and operate those stores at a loss each year.  They want people to learn to play, and to learn about the game, but they don't want to compete with Rogue Trader stores in the area.  If we wanted (and since I just thought of it, we freaking should) I'm sure Gallops could ask the new GW store up in Atlanta to advertise all our leagues for us.<br>
<br>
If taking 5 books down off Gallops' online store is the price to be paid to end competition from online discounters, so be it.  Oh, and never underestimate GW's ferocity in litigating IP infringments...all of the discounters are based in the US, so GW can find them easily and cancel their direct purchases - at the very least.  They've also already told Alliance to expect a shitlist of online vendors that Alliance will have to stop selling GW product to or lose their GW contract altogether.<br>
<br>
My vote?  Good thing.  Brick and Mortar is where it's at for this hobby, and a vendor who offers 40% discounts without providing any gaming or socializing location at all only injures the various hobbies. <p><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:#DC143C;font-size:small;">Bungabunga &lt;Heavy Hand&gt;<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->53 Troll Beastlord<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->&quot;Have Gator, will travel.&quot;<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
